description: Latin Gnatho, name of a parasitical character in the Eunuchus of Terence, Ancient Greek γνάθων (gnáthōn) (probably from the genitive plural form of γνάθος (gnáthos, “jaw”)- the genitive singular, γνάθου (gnáthou, “jaw”), was used adjectivally with the meaning "greedy"); hence, a parasite in general.

adjectives.description: gnathonic (comparative more gnathonic, superlative most gnathonic)
